goals.question: What is the gender distribution in the population data?
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the gender distribution of the population and identify any gender imbalances.

goals.rationale: This visualization will help us identify which age and gender groups have the highest and lowest population sizes.

goals.question: What is the correlation between age and population size?

goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the relationship between age and population size and identify any age groups that have a higher or lower population size than expected.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['year'] = pd.to_datetime(data['year'], format='%Y', errors='coerce')
    data = data[pd.notna(data['year'])]
    
    total_population = data.groupby('year')['people'].sum().reset_index()
    
    plt.plot(total_population['year'], total_population['people'])
    plt.xlabel('Year')
    plt.ylabel('Population')
    plt.title('What is the trend of population growth over time?', wrap=True)
    plt.legend(['Population'])
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.hist(data['age'], bins=20, color='blue', alpha=0.7, edgecolor='black')
    plt.xlabel('Age')
    plt.ylabel('Frequency')
    plt.title('What is the distribution of age in the population data?', wrap=True)
    plt.axvline(data['age'].median(), color='red', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=2, label=f"Median Age: {data['age'].median():.2f}")
    plt.legend()
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    gender_counts = data['sex'].value_counts()
    gender_counts.index = ['Male', 'Female']
    
    ax = gender_counts.plot(kind='bar', color=['blue', 'red'])
    plt.title('What is the gender distribution in the population data?')
    plt.xlabel('Gender')
    plt.ylabel('Number of People')
    plt.xticks(rotation=0)
    plt.legend(['Gender'])
    
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
import seaborn as sns

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['age_group'] = pd.cut(data['age'], bins=range(0, 100, 10), right=False)
    avg_population = data.groupby(['year', 'age_group', 'sex'])['people'].mean().reset_index()
    
    pivot_table = avg_population.pivot_table(index=['age_group', 'sex'], columns='year', values='people')
    
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 6))
    sns.heatmap(pivot_table, cmap='coolwarm', ax=ax)
    
    plt.title('What is the average population size by age and gender?', wrap=True)
    plt.xlabel('Year')
    plt.ylabel('Age Group and Gender (1 for male, 2 for female)')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    scatter = ax.scatter(data['age'], data['people'], c=data['sex'], cmap='viridis', alpha=0.5)
    legend1 = ax.legend(*scatter.legend_elements(), title="Sex")
    ax.add_artist(legend1)
    plt.xlabel('Age')
    plt.ylabel('Population Size')
    plt.title('What is the correlation between age and population size?', wrap=True)
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
